From: Mark Crispon <e-mail-address.suppressed@nospam>
Date: Sun, 2 Nov 1997 13:09:51 -0800 (PST)
Subject: Minnow

The Minnow project was cancelled before it was capable of running an OS.  The
furthest they got was running EDDT; that means about 10% of the work to
getting a real machine (having worked on both SC-30 and PDP-10 emulator, I can
tell you that getting EDDT to work is easy).
 
Pete Hurley (I think) told an interesting story about the Minnow.  The board
was being sent to the solder bath to solder the ICs, and true to its name it
dived into the solder!
 
As far as I know, the Minnow's final resting place was as a wall decoration.
 
I think, but I'm not sure, that Dolphin had gotten further along before it was
cancelled.  Dolphin would have been a major disaster for DEC marketing; it
would have competed with the VAX 780 at similar pricing but much better
performance.  Jupiter was scaled much larger (as it turned out, too large for
DEC's expertise) to avoid that problem.
