Technically, of course, I should have written "WAITS" instead of "SAIL"--the
official name of the operating system was the former.  There were at least four
different things all called "SAIL" relating to the Stanford Artificial Intelli-
gence Laboratory:  The Lab itself, the PDP-10 owned by the Lab and attached to
the ARPANET (later Internet), for a while the OS on that -10, and an Algol 60
derivative (with the "LEAP" data structures, whatever that may mean) where it
stood for "Stanford Artificial Intelligence Language."

WAITS has been relegated to a set of backup tapes written with the DART program
(a SAIL-only utility), archived somewhere by the Computer Science department at
Stanford.  Before being reminded about the hobbyist license for 36-bit OSes, I
was concerned about the fact that WAITS started out as the PDP-10 Monitor
version 3.27 (before it was renamed to "Tops-10" by DEC!), with the Tops-20
PHYSIO adapted to WAITS instead of the Tops-10 stuff; I guess that if one could
demonstrate an executed license, and the sources were available, one could see
them, if Stanford would allow their copyrighted parts to be released...  (Same
problems as at MIT, you know.)

It's complex, isn't it? ;-)
