Trivia follows (mostly for Joe but also for the [several] other PDP-10
and TOPS-20 fans out there):

Re:
| > And let's not forget the PDP-10/DEC-20 (KA,KI,KS,KL processors) with
| > its 36-bit word length
| 
| Ah... Now _there_ was a machine, though I don't recall a KS model.
| How did that differ from the KI/KL?

There were 4 (actually 5) models from DEC:

1. the original PDP-6 with transistors.  Paging modification to this became
   the KA PDP-10

2. next generation used ICs, hence the "I" in "KI"

3. the next and most advanced model was the KS in which the "S" stood for
   Schottky.  This was actually the physically smallest model, all self-
   contained in one cabinet about the size of a 17 cu ft refrigerator.
   Disks were still external (RP06, RP07, RP20, etc.)

4. the last model (due to cancelling the Jupiter) was the KL CPU in which
   the "L" stood for its use of ECL logic.  The power supply in that sucker
   had capacitors the size of pony kegs.  :-)

   Architecturally the KS was more advanced than the KL, but the KL ran
   like a bat out of hell.

Other notes:

A. there was a floating-point bug in the KS which never got fixed due to
   hard-coded microcode not being (economically) changeable.

B. three variants of this family:

   1. Foonly (ex-Stanford) made several models (F-1, F-4, etc.) which were
      incredible.  I saw the first one while visiting Stanford one day in
      the LOTS facility, so I opened it up to see what was inside.  Cabinet
      (just one!) was almost empty, yet this was 4x more powerful than the
      DEC-2060s I had at the time.  I later used one F-4 on a contract for
      the US Navy.

      Foonly was based in Palo Alto.

   2. Systems Concepts model SC-1.  Incredible piece of hardware and in
      direct competition with Foonly.  Trouble was the company was run
      totally by engineer-types and they never would solidify the design
      and get it to market, so their funds eventually ran out.  They really
      needed some MBA types in that company to sell the damned thing.

      Systems Concepts was located in San Francisco.

   3. Name escapes me, but it was up in Oregon and the company was formed
      by Len Bosack and Sandy Lerner (yes, the 2 who started Cisco).  They
      made a desktop DEC-20 (about PC-sized) that actually ran TOPS-20.
      Never saw a commercial (and marketed) version of this one, though,
      which is a shame as I would have bought one just to be able to run
      the ORIGINAL versions of Zork, Haunt, dungeon, Fisk, etc. at home.  :-)

Thad


