Last week, Tim Litt called me to tell me that KL1026 (nee' GIDNEY) 
was to be turned off and scrapped.  When Jim died, I had expressed 
a desire to see a PDP-10 one last time, so Tim thought I would like
to visit the -10 before it went away.  Needless to say, this news was
upsetting.  I cried off and on until I went to see the -10 on 5-Dec-97.  
And this is how I did it.

Underneath my sweat shirt, I wore the first tee-shirt that the TOPS-10
folks had produced.  Its front had the words "THE REPORTS OF MY
DEATH HAVE BEEN GREATLY EXAGGERATED" and the back
had a dipiction of a video terminal with the words (DEC system-10
continued).  I fought long and hard to this put on the back; but that's
another story.  In my carry-all, I placed the picture of Jim and Tony
in front of CHIP that had been taken at a DECUS.

Tim met me in the lobby of MRO-1 and walked me to the machine
room.  As soon as I entered the room, the smells hit me.  I had
never before realized that a -10 had a unique smell.  All kinds of
memories started to manifest themselves.  I almost expected to
see Jim and Tony debugging at the console.

The system was orange (darn) and was down.  Apparently, the
system pack had been munged, an RP06 was dead (one of two),
the tape drives weren't working, and the floppy drives didn't seem
to work.  Tim was trying to get the system into a state so that
some of the information on the packs could be saved to media
readable by other non-PDP-10 systems.  This was the second
time that I had observed a PDP-10 not cooperating when it
was scheduled to be torn apart System 40/2 was the other one;
in System 40's case the KL and the KI systems both helped
to prevent its demise (but that's yet another story).

Tim finally got a monitor loaded from a KLAD pack but that pack
was so old the microcodes for the tapes weren't in it.  He finally
found a KLAD (after I had reassured him that I had KLADs built
so that all hardware could be detected and found) that finally
could see the tape controller.  But the tapes didn't work--lots
of hard errors.  

I went into the back room where lots of tapes and packs were
kept.  There was a hit and miss of RE tapes.  I was surprised
at my ability to figure out what the tapes were and what should
be on them.  I had thought that I had forgotten all that stuff.

For some reason, Tim wanted to boot the TOAD (yup, I got to
meet one :-)) so I played with the -10 on the console for while.
Just doing a directory of SYS: brought back knowledge.  I
ran DDT and was surprised that I could do DDT commands 
without a cheat sheet.  I tried to solve a conundrum that
somebody had given me but failed.  I opened a file with
TECO.  And, while I was doing all this playing, I occasionally
petted the -10.

Meanwhile, Tim had forgotten his password on the TOAD.  I
watched him boot up TOPS-20 with the /DDT switch and 
look at locations.  Remember all the times we used to watch
Jim and Tony debug the monitor on Wednesday mornings?
There was a taste of that in the air.

Tim finally succeeded in getting a magtape drive to work on
the TOAD and successfully read an REtape to disk and 
save that info to another magtape.  Those TOADs have a 
nice PDP-10 feel to them.  I do wish there were lights [wistful 
emoticon here].

By that time, the pain that this disease has bestowed upon me had 
become too severe for me to stay any longer, so I left.   I don't know 
if there was any kind of party like the one they had for KL2102.  I 
didn't go to that party; I just watched the party from afar for a couple 
of minutes.  (I said good-bye later to KL2102 when there was nobody 
around.)

This is the end of an era that should never be forgotten.  I'm just
glad that Jim and Tony didn't have to see it.

/BAH



