    Well, my take on it is that the "One Company, One Strategy, One
    Message" directive of the mid '80s was the death knell of the
    company.  Of course, it was part of the justification for killing
    off the 36-bit line, but that's only a small part of the problem.
    DEC could have prospered very well without 10/20 line, sentiments
    of this group notwithstanding, but it would eventually need
    something beside or beyond VAX/VMS, and nobody was allowed to say
    or even think that, much less do anything to move in that
    direction.

    DEC grew and became successful originally because it was a hotbed
    of ideas, a lot of them got tried, and some of them were very
    good.  Product line managers had a lot of autonomy, and yeah, so
    they competed with one another, but so what?  One or the other of
    them would get the business, and so DEC got the business.
    Somehow, by the mid-80's Ken Olsen developed delusions of
    infallability or something, in marked contrast to the caution that
    he was formerly well known for, and promulgated this One Egg, One
    Basket strategy (as we all called it).  Of course, the company
    didn't begin to decline immediately, but I would say that DEC's
    peak was around 1987 -- only a few years after monotheism took
    root.

    The idea that DEC as a whole could only do one thing, or that
    everything had to fit into some overarching strategy, remained a
    totally ingrained part of the corporate culture up through the
    time I left in 1992.  The result was that DEC stopped doing
    aggressive new things or was years late doing them.  The corporate
    culture was wedded to VAX and VMS as if they would live forever.
    Even Alpha was initially, and through most of its design period,
    intended as a faster hardware engine for VMS.

    A piece of this shifting mindset that, I believe, led to DEC's
    decline included that we had to stop being a "technology push"
    company and start building what marketing said was needed.  Doing
    things because they were neat and with the expectation that they
    might create new markets and new business became politically
    incorrect!  'Course, DEC never had marketing that was worth squat
    anyhow, and the history of the past decade is that people make BIG
    money by doing new things and creating new markets.  Even if you
    look at the infamously marketing-oriented companies like Microsoft
    and Compaq, you see that good marketing means selling the s**t out
    of what you have, not inventing the products that are going to be
    pivotal in 3 or 4 years.

    It is interesting to compare HP and DEC.  HP, like DEC, had a
    culture of having multiple product lines that pursue their
    business with much autonomy and aggressiveness.  They kept the
    company structed that way, however.  I think it was David Packard
    who said, "you've got to eat your own lunch, or your competitors
    will eat it for you."  In other words, you have to continually
    bring out new products that beat your existing ones, or your
    competitors will do it.  In the late 80's, DEC and HP were about
    the same size, but, funny thing! HP has continued to grow it's
    revenues by double-digit percentages each year, while DEC's
    revenue has been flat for a decade.  HP now has over twice the
    revenue of DEC, and their stock price has increased several fold.
    DEC stock price (before the Compaq deal) was about 1/4 of what it
    was in 1987.

    I believe the fundamental reason that DEC topped out in 1987 is
    that KO decided all of DEC had to fit in one box and march to one
    tune.  Many good projects were killed off in that era -- projects
    that would have given the company life after VAX but were killed
    because nobody was allowed to imagine life after VAX until it was
    too late.
    
    
    dlm
    


