Just to add a bit more pedantry to the discussion:

When the DECsystem-10 name came about, the slash disappeared in the model names.
Bentley College (my alma mater) had a DECsystem-1070.

Also, as BAH mentioned, the 1077 was AMP.  The SMP system was called the
1099, I believe.  Of course that may have been the version that allowed
1091 style systems to participate in SMP. (1091s came with internal memory
channels, and therefore couldn't run SMP, which required external channels
and shared external memory boxes.)

Entertaining tidbit: towards the end, the third machine in the
KL1026/KL1042/KL2476 tri-SMP development system was a 1091, with both
internal _and_ external channels!  You could take it out of tri-SMP and run
it standalone by just switching which channels were configured via RSX-20F
commands.

What was even more entertaining was that the system had access to the same
CI-based disks (RA60 and RA81 models, which supported 18-bit sectors) that
the rest of the gang did.  All the disks were connected to two HSC50
controllers, one via the A path, the other via the B path.  If I remember
correctly, 1026 and 1042 were connected to one HSC, and 2476 was connected
to the other one.  In tri-SMP operation, you could load-balance the disks
across the CPUs by having some disks forced to the A path and others forced
to the B path.  (Forcing was done by making sure that only one of the
A-path/B-path buttons was pressed in on the front panel.)

If I remember correctly, the steps to take KL2476 standalone and mount a
couple of the SMP system's disks there went like this:

0. Make sure that any disks that were to STAY on 1026/1042 were forced to
the A path.  The Monitor would notice that the path to 2476 had gone away
and would transparently initiate a new virtual circuit to the other path.

1. Tell OPR to go into CONFIG mode and remove CPU2.

        Any disks that were only visible to the system via that CPU would
        be automatically dismounted.  This included the RP06 that held KL2476's
        RSX20F front-end file system, since that disk was dual-ported between
        the PDP-11 and the -10.
        The CPU would be removed.

2. Put a pre-built KL2476 standalone system disk on kl2476's dual-ported RP06 
   spindle, and boot.  The RSX20F on that disk was configured for a system with
   internal channels only, and therefore set up the machine to ignore the
   external channels, and the memory thereon.


Anyone who remembers care to comment?

