>The question becomes.... What was Stopgap?  A more primitive
>editor than SOS?

Stopgap (and SOS) came from the Stanford AI Lab.  It was called
that because it was a non-display-oriented editor thrown together
quickly when the PDP-6 (I'm pretty sure this was before the -10)
came into use.  They already knew (from experience on the PDP-1)
that display editing was the way to go, but it took a while to
get TVEDIT done.  [This is secondhand information, since all that
happened before I came to Stanford, but I'm pretty sure about it.]

The reason Stopgap lasted long enough to have a Son is that for
many years, real display support at SAIL was limited to terminals
in the building; people used SOS when editing from home.


