ORNL was the first customer installed Tri-SMP system.  But Jim and I
built the first working one in the MRO lab.

I was working on a little AD project, the idea being to closely couple
a TOPS10 system with a TOPS20 system.  Fred Engel was working the TOPS20
side.  About the same time, Jim and Duane were talking about going to more
than 2 processors for ORNL.

The master/slave monitors used CP1SER which really didn't work for more
than two processors.  For SMP, I upgraded it to CPNSER and while it worked
fine for 2 systems, it was really never tested with more.  The KL-10
memory boxes really couldn't handle more than two without performance
degradation (only 4 arbitrated ports and the processors needed 2 each for
interleaved fetch).  Since our development machines were also the main
user machines, they were unwilling to recable the memory boxes.

Jim and I thought we could kill two birds if we took KL2136 (I think) and
had Field Service install an external memory interface (forget the option
number) and use two priority ports of the external memory boxes.  Since
we could enable or disable the internal memory of the -20 with the console,
this would give us a system for my debugging (TOPS10 on two, TOPS20 on the
third), or for Tri-SMP debugging using only the shared external memory.

My AD project got canned (and rightfully so!) but the lab setup was used
to run Tri-SMP occasionally.  We would periodically boot the Tri SMP monitor
and later remove the -20 system with System Sleep/Config.

ORNL used AMPEX memory at that time and had more arbitrated ports available
so they didn't have the potential memory starvation problems we had in the
lab. Jim championed the Tri SMP project to marketing and they decided it
had enough merit to sell.  I forget how much in funding we got to do a
project that was already done and tested.  Duane, on the other hand, just
couldn't stand by and be running a supported configuration, so he bought
a 4th processor and eventually a 5th.

