<snip>

When we did SMP, Jim and Tony were very careful to _not_ preclude
more than two CPUs.  They wanted to have 1-8 CPUs supported from
the beginning, but we had our rules about not supporting something
that we couldn't test, debug, reproduce problems, etc.  Since Duane
started talking about upgrading to 3 whilst Jim and Tony were 
developing for only two, Jim tried to get the product line to agree to
support for tri-SMP.  That idea was nixed in flames; they did not
buy our argument that, if there was a tri-SMP dependent problem, we
could debug it at ORNL.  

So, what we did was very carefully keep all documentation from 
saying two or dual or any limitation on the number of CPUs 
supported.  (And that was a constant battle with documentation, 
the product line people, and marketing.)  Instead of having a 
number put in the docs, we insisted that the term "multi-" be 
used.  The only place where two was mentioned was the beware 
file (remember those?) and, I believe, there were only three
instances where dual had to be changed to multi.

So, the plan was that, after we shipped 7.01, the first SMP monitor,
the only things that had to be done for supporting tri-SMP were:

1.  Change the beware file from dual to multi; estimated manpower 
5 seconds using a TECO macro.

2.  Write an SPD; estimated manpower 1 week.

3.  Resubmit the CPNSER tape to SDC with the changed beware file; no
changes to the source; estimated time 1 month for Release Engineering's 
complete process of submission.

4. No documentation changes were required; estimated manpower was 0.

So there we were; 7.01 had shipped; Duane had already added the 3rd
CPU and Software Engineering had successfully argued that it should
be supported.  Jim had the beware file modified and the files had
been handed to Magee for the tape making process.   Then somebody
got the great idea that we had to go through the project notebook
cycle (whatever the hell they called it--I forget now) that a major
release went through in order to get all the powers-that-wanna-be
to agree that "this is good".

It took Jim 9 months to push through the submission; and, when Jim
pushed, things happened.   We could not believe what kind of release
mess we (DEC) had created for ourselves.  It was our first awareness
that this process was actually designed to hinder productivity.  Jim,
Tony, and I had a bout of depression and I had my initial prescience 
of the future of TOPS10.  I began to fight for our existence.  We lost.

/BAH


