including all of the complex job scheduling that GALAXY attempted to
implement.  The story at the time was not that this was included in a
written contract, but had been given verbally to the representatives of the
University, and only after the contract was signed did DEC find out that the
verbal commitments were considered binding in Norway.  The result of not
having the functions was that DEC had to deliver a lot of extra hardware
(tape drives, and perhaps disk drives) to allow the job mix to run without
the manual scheduling until the functions were available.  The amount of
investment DEC had sitting in Oslo was supposedly one of the main reasons
why there was such a push to get GALAXY shipping, even though the first
field test release wouldn't stay running for 24 hours.

Nick Bush






